# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: drug-delivery-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Extended-release dosage consists of either sustained-release (SR) or controlled-release (CR) dosage.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] SR maintains drug release over a sustained period but not at a constant rate.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] CR maintains drug release over a sustained period at a nearly constant rate.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Sometimes these and other terms are treated as synonyms, but the United States Food and Drug Administration has in fact defined most of these as different concepts.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Sometimes the term "depot tablet" is used, by analogy to the term for an injection formulation of a drug which releases slowly over time, but this term is not medically or pharmaceutically standard for oral medication.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] For example, orally administered extended-release morphine can enable certain chronic pain patients to take only 1–2 tablets per day, rather than needing to redose every 4–6 hours as is typical with standard-release morphine tablets.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Most commonly it refers to time-dependent release in oral dose formulations.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Timed release has several distinct variants such as sustained release where prolonged release is intended, pulse release, delayed release (e.g. to target different regions of the GI tract) etc.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] A distinction of controlled release is that it not only prolongs action, but it attempts to maintain drug levels within the therapeutic window to avoid potentially hazardous peaks in drug concentration following ingestion or injection and to maximize therapeutic efficiency.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] In addition to pills, the mechanism can also apply to capsules and injectable drug carriers (that often have an additional release function), forms of controlled release medicines include gels, implants and devices (e.g. the vaginal ring and contraceptive implant) and transdermal patches.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Examples for cosmetic, personal care, and food science applications often centre on odour or flavour release.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] The release technology scientific and industrial community is represented by the Controlled Release Society (CRS).
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] The CRS is the worldwide society for delivery science and technologies.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] CRS serves more than 1,600 members from more than 50 countries.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Two-thirds of CRS membership is represented by industry and one-third represents academia and government.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] CRS is affiliated with the *Journal of Controlled Release* and *Drug Delivery and Translational Research* scientific journals.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] The terminology used in modified-release formulations is not standardized, which can be cause for confusion, misreading and prescription errors.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Common terminology is summarized in the table below.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Not to be confused with SA for *Short-Acting*.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Not to be confused with XS, or *Extra Strength*.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Today, most time-release drugs are formulated so that the active ingredient is embedded in a matrix of insoluble substance(s) (various: some acrylics, even chitin; these substances are often patented) such that the dissolving drug must find its way out through the holes.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] In some SR formulations, the drug dissolves into the matrix, and the matrix physically swells to form a gel, allowing the drug to exit through the gel's outer surface.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Micro-encapsulation is also regarded as a more complete technology to produce complex dissolution profiles.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] The biological half-life of the drug refers to the drug's elimination from the bloodstream which can be caused by metabolism, urine, and other forms of excretion.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] If the active compound has a long half-life (over 6 hours), it is sustained on its own.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] If the active compound has a short half-life, it would require a large amount to maintain a prolonged effective dose.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] In this case, a broad therapeutic window is necessary to avoid toxicity; otherwise, the risk is unwarranted and another mode of administration would be recommended.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Appropriate half-lives used to apply sustained methods are typically 3–4 hours and a drug dose greater than 0.5 grams is too high.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] The therapeutic index also factors whether a drug can be used as a time release drug.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] A drug with a thin therapeutic range, or small therapeutic index, will be determined unfit for a sustained release mechanism in partial fear of dose dumping which can prove fatal at the conditions mentioned.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] For a drug that is made to be released over time, the objective is to stay within the therapeutic range as long as needed.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] There are many different methods used to obtain a sustained release.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Diffusion systems' rate release is dependent on the rate at which the drug dissolves through a barrier which is usually a type of polymer.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Diffusion systems can be broken into two subcategories, reservoir devices and matrix devices.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Dissolution systems must have the system dissolved slowly in order for the drug to have sustained release properties which can be achieved by using appropriate salts and/or derivatives as well as coating the drug with a dissolving material.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] It is used for drug compounds with high solubility in water.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] When the drug is covered with some slow dissolving coat, it will eventually release the drug.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Instead of diffusion, the drug release depends on the solubility and thickness of the coating.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Because of this mechanism, the dissolution will be the rate limiting factor for drug release.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Dissolution systems can be broken down to subcategories called reservoir devices and matrix devices.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Osmotic controlled-release oral delivery systems (OROS) have the form of a rigid tablet with a semi-permeable outer membrane and one or more small laser drilled holes in it.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] As the tablet passes through the body, water is absorbed through the semipermeable membrane via osmosis, and the resulting osmotic pressure is used to push the active drug through the opening(s) in the tablet.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] OROS is a trademarked name owned by ALZA Corporation, which pioneered the use of osmotic pumps for oral drug delivery.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Osmotic release systems have a number of major advantages over other controlled-release mechanisms.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] They are significantly less affected by factors such as pH, food intake, GI motility, and differing intestinal environments.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Using an osmotic pump to deliver drugs has additional inherent advantages regarding control over drug delivery rates.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] This allows for much more precise drug delivery over an extended period of time, which results in much more predictable pharmacokinetics.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] However, osmotic release systems are relatively complicated, somewhat difficult to manufacture, and may cause irritation or even blockage of the GI tract due to prolonged release of irritating drugs from the non-deformable tablet.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] In the ion-exchange method, the resins are cross-linked water-insoluble polymers that contain ionisable functional groups that form a repeating pattern of polymers, creating a polymer chain.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] The drug is attached to the resin and is released when an appropriate interaction of ions and ion exchange groups occur.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] The area and length of the drug release and number of cross-link polymers dictate the rate at which the drug is released, determining the SR effect.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] A floating system is a system where it floats on gastric fluids due to low density.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] The density of the gastric fluids is about 1 g/mL; thus, the drug/tablet administered must have a smaller density.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] The buoyancy will allow the system to float to the top of the stomach and release at a slower rate without worry of excreting it.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] This system requires that there are enough gastric fluids present as well as food.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Many types of forms of drugs use this method such as powders, capsules, and tablets.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Bio-adhesive systems generally are meant to stick to mucus and can be favorable for mouth based interactions due to high mucus levels in the general area but not as simple for other areas.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Magnetic materials can be added to the drug so another magnet can hold it from outside the body to assist in holding the system in place.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] However, there is low patient compliance with this system.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] The matrix system is the mixture of materials with the drug, which will cause the drug to slow down.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] However, this system has several subcategories: hydrophobic matrices, lipid matrices, hydrophilic matrices, biodegradable matrices, and mineral matrices.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Examples of stimuli that may be used to bring about release include pH, enzymes, light, magnetic fields, temperature, ultrasonics, osmosis, cellular traction forces, and electronic control of MEMS and NEMS.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Spherical hydrogels, in micro-size (50-600 μm diameter) with 3-dimensional cross-linked polymer, can be used as drug carrier to control the release of the drug.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] They may possess a negative charge as example DC-beads.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] By ion-exchange mechanism, a large amount of oppositely charged amphiphilic drugs can be loaded inside these microgels.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Then, the release of these drugs can be controlled by a specific triggering factor like pH, ionic strength or temperature.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Some time release formulations do not work properly if split, such as controlled-release tablet coatings, while other formulations such as micro-encapsulation still work if the microcapsules inside are swallowed whole.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Among the health information technology (HIT) that pharmacists use are medication safety tools to help manage this problem.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] For example, the ISMP "do not crush" list can be entered into the system so that warning stickers can be printed at the point of dispensing, to be stuck on the pill bottle.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Pharmaceutical companies that do not supply a range of half-dose and quarter-dose versions of time-release tablets can make it difficult for patients to be slowly tapered off their drugs.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] The earliest SR drugs are associated with a patent in 1938 by Israel Lipowski, who coated pellets which led to coating particles.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Delivery is usually effected by dissolution, degradation, or disintegration of an excipient in which the active compound is formulated.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/controlled-release] Enteric coating and other encapsulation technologies can further modify release profiles.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Drug delivery is closely linked with dosage form and route of administration, the latter of which is sometimes considered to be part of the definition.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Although the terms are often used interchangeably, they represent distinct concepts.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] The route of administration refers specifically to the path by which a drug enters the body, such as oral, parenteral, or transdermal.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] In contrast, the dosage form refers to the physical form in which the drug is manufactured and delivered, such as tablets, capsules, patches, inhalers or injectable solutions.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] These are various dosage forms and technologies which include but not limited to nanoparticles, liposomes, microneedles, and hydrogels that can be used to enhance therapeutic efficacy and safety.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] The same route can accommodate multiple dosage forms; for example, the oral route may involve tablet, capsule, or liquid suspension.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] While the transdermal route may use a patch, gel, or cream.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Drug delivery incorporates both of these concepts while encompassing a broader scope, including the design and engineering of systems that operate within or across these routes.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Common routes of administration include oral, parenteral (injected), sublingual, topical, transdermal, nasal, ocular, rectal, and vaginal.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] However, modern drug delivery continue to expand the possibilities of these routes through novel and hybrid approaches.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Since the approval of the first controlled-release formulation in the 1950s, research into new delivery systems has been progressing, as opposed to new drug development which has been declining.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Several factors may be contributing to this shift in focus.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] One of the driving factors is the high cost of developing new drugs.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] A 2013 review found the cost of developing a delivery system was only 10% of the cost of developing a new pharmaceutical.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] A more recent study found the median cost of bringing a new drug to market was $985 million in 2020, but did not look at the cost of developing drug delivery systems.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Other factors that have potentially influenced the increase in drug delivery system development may include the increasing prevalence of both chronic and infectious diseases, as well as a general increased understanding of the pharmacology, pharmacokinetics, and pharmacodynamics of many drugs.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Current efforts in drug delivery are vast and include topics such as controlled-release formulations, targeted delivery, nanomedicine, drug carriers, 3D printing, and the delivery of biologic drugs.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Nanotechnology is a broad field of research and development that deals with the manipulation of matter at the atomic or subatomic level.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] It is used in fields such as medicine, energy, aerospace engineering, and more.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] One of the applications of nanotechnology is in drug delivery.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] This is a process by which nanoparticles are used to carry and deliver drugs to a specific area in the body.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] There are several advantages of using nanotechnology for drug delivery, including precise targeting of specific cells, increased drug potency, and lowered toxicity to the cells that are targeted.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Nanoparticles can also carry vaccines to cells that might be hard to reach with traditional delivery methods.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] However, there are some concerns with the use of nanoparticles for drug delivery.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Some studies have shown that nanoparticles may contribute to the development of tumors in other parts of the body.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] There is also growing concern that nanoparticles may have harmful effects on the environment.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Despite these potential drawbacks, the use of nanotechnology in drug delivery is still a promising area for future research.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Targeted drug delivery is the delivery of a drug to its target site without having an effect on other tissues.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Interest in targeted drug delivery has grown drastically due to its potential implications in the treatment of cancers and other chronic diseases.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] In order to achieve efficient targeted delivery, the designed system must avoid the host's defense mechanisms and circulate to its intended site of action.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] A number of drug carriers have been studied to effectively target specific tissues, including liposomes, nanogels, and other nanotechnologies.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Drugs are delivered via scratch size patches known as Microneedle Patches.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Microneedle patches are an invention of the introduction of drugs into the skin with the help of minute needles that are not painful.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] The patches can deliver vaccines or medications, including insulin to diabetes patients into the blood or skin (Reinke et al., 2024).
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] They are easy to use and they could make people give treatments at home.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] However, such patches are very expensive and not easily accessible.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Controlled or modified-release formulations are designed to deliver medications at a steady rate over time, helping maintain consistent drug levels in the bloodstream.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] This steady release reduced how often patients need to take their medication and minimizes the ups and downs in drug concentration that can cause side effects or lower effectiveness.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] These systems often take the form of matrix tablets, osmotic pumps, and reservoir-type devices, all of which use physical or chemical barriers to regulate how the drug is released.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] This approach is especially useful for chronic conditions such as high blood pressure, diabetes, or chronic pain, where maintaining stable therapeutic levels is key to keeping symptoms under control.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] The concept of controlled-release medication dates back to the 1950s, when Dexedrine became the first such formulation on the market.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] This era saw the introduction of transdermal patches, which deliver drugs slowly through the skin.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] As technology progressed, new formulations were developed to match the specific properties of different drugs.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Examples include long-acting depot injections for medication like antipsychotics and hormone therapies, which remain effective for weeks or even months after a single dose.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Since the late 1990s, research has increasingly turned to nanotechnology as a way to improve controlled-released drug delivery.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Nanoparticles, tiny carriers engineered at a molecular level, can protect drugs from being broken down too quickly in the body, improve how well they're absorbed, and deliver them directly to the tissues where they're needed.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] This targeted delivery not only reduces side effects but also helps patients stay on track with their treatments.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] These advances in nanotechnology are transforming the landscape of drug delivery and are emphasizing the importance of developing the next generation of CR systems.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] The use of nanotechnology into drug delivery has opened the door to new possibilities, particularly with the development of nanoparticle-based controlled-release systems.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] These systems are designed to deliver drugs more precisely and over longer periods of time helping with targeted sites and therapeutic effects.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Tiny carriers, such as liposomes, dendrimers, and polymeric nanoparticles, can hold medication and release them at controlled rates.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Some are even engineered to respond to specific conditions in the body.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] For instance, acidic microenvironment commonly found in tumor tissues can be used to trigger drug release at the site needed.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] This targeted approach helps minimize side effects by limiting exposure to the rest the body.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Recent studies have shown the effectiveness of smart nanoparticles that respond to biological cues, such as pH or redox conditions, thereby delivering drugs more precisely to tumor sites.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] For instance, pH-sensitive nanoparticles take advantage of the lower pH in tumor cells to release the drugs, which boost effectiveness while protecting healthy cells.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Additionally, the use of biocompatible materials and switching the nanoparticle surfaces have improved their accuracy and release of delivery systems.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Advances in design have also made it possible to create multi-functional nanoparticles that are capable of handling tough challenges like multi-drug resistance in cancer.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] These systems can carry more than one type of drug, targeting specific molecules, which helps to deliver a stronger punch to tumor tissues.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Altogether, these breakthroughs point to a potential for nanoparticle-based controlled-release therapies in the fields of cancer therapy and personalized medicine.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] In recent years, advances in smart polymers and hydrogels have brought major improvements to how drugs are delivered in controlled-released systems.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] These materials are unique in that they can respond to changes inside the body, like shifts in pH, temperature, and glucose levels, making it possible to fine-tune when and how much of a drug is released.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] For example, some hydrogels are designed to expand or contract based on these internal signals, which helps regulate the speed of drug release.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] This kind of precision helps improves therapeutic treatment and reduces side effects.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] These responsive materials are useful for managing chronic condition like diabetes, where glucose-responsive hydrogels can adjust insulin release based on blood sugar levels.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Many scientists worked to create oral formulations that could maintain a constant drug level because of the ability of drug release at a zero-order rate blood's concentration.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] However, a few physiological restrictions made it challenging to create such oral formulations.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] First, because the lower parts of the intestine have a decreased capacity for absorption, the medication absorption typically declines as an oral formulation moves from the stomach to the intestine.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] The decreased drug amount released from the formulation over time frequently made this condition worse.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Phenylpropanolamine HCl release from was the only instance of sustaining consistent blood concentration for roughly 16 hours.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Delivering biological drugs such as peptides, proteins, antibodies, and genetic material, comes with unique challenges.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Because of their large size and electrical charges, these molecules are often poorly absorbed and easily broken down by enzymes in the body.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] To overcome these hurdles, scientists have been developing advanced delivery methods using tools like liposomes, nanoparticles, fusion proteins, and protein-based nanocages.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Some strategies take inspiration from how toxins naturally enter cells by adapting those mechanisms for therapeutic use.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Among the macromolecules studied, RNA delivery has made progress, especially with the success of RNA-based COVID-19 vaccines.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] While protein and DNA delivery have shown progress, proteins in live animals and DNA in lab settings, delivering these large molecules, still remain a complex task.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Although oral administration is generally preferred by patients for convenience, it's rarely effective for biologics due to poor absorption.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] That being said, innovative technologies such as enzyme inhibitors, permeation enhancers, lipid-based nanoparticles, and microneedles are being used to improve oral bioavailability for these drugs.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] One of the recent developments that has been successful is the use of lipid nanoparticles (LNPs) to deliver messenger RNA (mRNA).
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] LNPs protect fragile mRNA from degradation and escape from endosomes so it can reach the cytoplasm and produce proteins.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] This delivery method gained worldwide recognition during COVID-19 pandemic with the approval of mRNA vaccines from Pfizer-BioTech and Moderna.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] The rapid rollout of these vaccines proved that LNPs are not only effective but also scalable for mass production and global use.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Looking beyond vaccines, mRNA therapies are now being explored for a range of therapeutic applications including cancer immunotherapy, genetic disorders, and other infectious diseases.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Researchers are also testing alternative delivery systems, like exosomes and new types of nanoparticles, to make mRNA therapies safer and more efficient.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] However, challenges remain, as mRNA is highly sensitive to environmental conditions.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] To address this, ongoing research is expanding into new administration routes including inhalable or oral mNRA formulations.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] This could reduce production costs and make these therapies more accessible to the world.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Delivering medications to the brain has long been a significant challenge in treating neurological diseases.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] The main reason lies in the blood-brain barrier (BBB), a highly selective, protective layer that shields the brain from toxins and pathogens in the bloodstream.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] While the BBB is crucial for maintaining brain health, it also makes it difficult for most therapeutic drugs to reach their target, especially in conditions like Alzheimer's and Parkinson's disease.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] As a result, conventional drug delivery methods often fall short, either causing unwanted side effects or failing to deliver a high enough concentration to be effective.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] To address this, researchers have turned to nanoparticles, tiny engineered carriers designed to sneak past the BBB and deliver drugs directly to the brain tissue These particles can be tailored to take advantage of the body's own transport systems.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] For example, by attaching certain molecules to their surfaces, nanoparticles can trigger receptor-mediated transcytosis, a natural process that allows them to pass through cells lining the BBB and enter the brain.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] This kind of targeted delivery helps reduce the drug's exposure to the rest of the body, lowering the risk of side effects and increasing concentration where it matters most.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] So far, this strategy has shown promise in delivering treatments to the brain for conditions like Alzheimer's and Parkinson's disease.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Several types of nanoparticles are being studied for this purpose.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Liposomes, for instance, are small vesicles that can carry drugs and be modified to circulate longer or home in on specific brain regions.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Dendrimers, with their tree-like structure, can hold multiple drug molecules and targeting agents at once.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Polymeric nanoparticles, made from biodegradable materials like polylactic acid (PLA) or polylactic-co-glycolic acid (PLGA), can be engineered to release drugs over time in a controlled way.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Solid lipid nanoparticles offer another alternative, combining biocompatibility with the ability to cross barriers more efficiently.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Altogether, these advances are paving the way for more effective and precise treatments for a range of neurological disorders.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Nanotechnology helps to transfer medicine to specific places in the body.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Drug delivery in new forms with the assistance of minute particles, like liposomes or polymeric micelles.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] These particles support the drugs by preventing disintegration and enhancing functionality (Islam et al., 2025).
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] An example would be, they can distribute cancer drugs to the tumors, which reduce the side effects.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Researchers also come up with particles, which release drugs when going through certain conditions like heat or light.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Despite the nature of this technology, it remains expensive and needs further safety studies.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] In the near future researchers say there will be a more advanced strategies of treatment such as the use nanomedicine and technology like artificial intelligence (Islam et al., 2025).
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] The drug delivery mechanisms have the potential to enhance the health of all parts of the world despite the fact that most of the advanced systems are quite costly to the poor nations.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Simple system, orals or skin patch, is more feasible in low resource countries.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Most countries have used vaccines that are administered orally to combat such diseases as polio (Yenet et al., 2023).
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] The government and the hospital organizations need to collaborate in order to reduce the cost and offer the new means of drug distribution that will allow giving the new medications everywhere.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Emerging drug delivery devices such as nanoparticles or gene therapies are highly dangerous in terms of safety and equity.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] For example, we should make sure that the treatments would not negatively affect the environment or cause any incidental side effects.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] The regulation of other agencies such as FDA are applied in the process of ensuring the safety of new practices but vary across countries (World Health Organization, 2024).
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] The government has the mandate of making sure that medicine is not only affordable to the wealthy members of the society, but also to the vulnerable ones as well.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] The issue of drug delivery has raised a number of ethical concerns with respect to patients and healthcare systems.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] One common concern is the accessibility of specific medications within a health organization.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Advanced delivery systems such as gene therapies, nanoparticles, or implants have been costly, and therefore, only patients within wealthy countries can afford them.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] This indicates that healthcare no longer considers equality and fairness.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Another ethical concern is the issue of privacy.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Digital tools have been used to determine and track patient medical adherence.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/drug-delivery] Although these tools may help improve patient welfare, they may also be used to expose patient data, and there are increasing insecurities regarding patients' personal information.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] A **liposome** is a small artificial vesicle, spherical in shape, having at least one lipid bilayer.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Due to their hydrophobicity and/or hydrophilicity, biocompatibility, particle size and many other properties, liposomes can be used as drug delivery vehicles for administration of pharmaceutical drugs and nutrients, such as lipid nanoparticles in mRNA vaccines, and DNA vaccines.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Liposomes can be prepared by disrupting biological membranes (such as by sonication).
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] A **nanoliposome** or **nanoliposomal vehicle** is a liposome in the nanoscale; in other words, it is a kind of nanocarrier involved in the processes of nanoencapsulation and nanodelivery.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Liposomes are most often composed of phospholipids, especially phosphatidylcholine, and cholesterol, but may also include other lipids, such as those found in egg and phosphatidylethanolamine, as long as they are compatible with lipid bilayer structure.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] A liposome design may employ surface ligands for attaching to desired cells or tissues.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Based on vesicle structure, there are seven main categories for liposomes: multilamellar large (MLV), oligolamellar (OLV), small unilamellar (SUV), medium-sized unilamellar (MUV), large unilamellar (LUV), giant unilamellar (GUV) and multivesicular vesicles (MVV).
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] The major types of liposomes are the multilamellar vesicle (MLV, with several lamellar phase lipid bilayers), the small unilamellar liposome vesicle (SUV, with one lipid bilayer), the large unilamellar vesicle (LUV), and the cochleate vesicle.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] A less desirable form is multivesicular liposomes in which one vesicle contains one or more smaller vesicles.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Liposomes should not be confused with lysosomes, or with micelles and reverse micelles.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] In contrast to liposomes, micelles typically contain a monolayer of fatty acids or surfactants.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] The word *liposome* derives from two Greek words: *lipo* ("fat") and *soma* ("body"); it is so named because its composition is primarily of phospholipid.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Liposomes were first described by British hematologist Alec Douglas Bangham in 1961 at the Babraham Institute, in Cambridge—findings that were published 1964.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] The discovery came about when Bangham and R.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Horne were testing the institute's new electron microscope by adding negative stain to dry phospholipids.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] The resemblance to the plasmalemma was obvious, and the microscopic pictures provided the first evidence that the cell membrane is a bilayer lipid structure.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] The following year, Bangham, his colleague Malcolm Standish, and Gerald Weissmann, an American physician, established the integrity of this closed, bilayer structure and its ability to release its contents following detergent treatment (structure-linked latency).
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] During a Cambridge pub discussion with Bangham, Weissmann first named the structures "liposomes" after something which laboratory had been studying, the lysosome: a simple organelle whose structure-linked latency could be disrupted by detergents and streptolysins.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Liposomes are readily distinguishable from micelles and hexagonal lipid phases through negative staining transmission electron microscopy.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Bangham, with colleagues Jeff Watkins and Standish, wrote the 1965 paper that effectively launched what would become the liposome "industry." Around that same time, Weissmann joined Bangham at the Babraham.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Later, Weissmann, then an emeritus professor at New York University School of Medicine, recalled the two of them sitting in a Cambridge pub, reflecting on the role of lipid sheets in separating the cell interior from its exterior milieu.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] This insight, they felt, would be to cell function what the discovery of the double helix had been to genetics.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] As Bangham had been calling his lipid structures "multilamellar smectic mesophases," or sometimes "Banghasomes," Weissmann proposed the more user-friendly term liposome.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] A liposome has an aqueous solution core surrounded by a hydrophobic membrane, in the form of a lipid bilayer; hydrophilic solutes dissolved in the core cannot readily pass through the bilayer.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Hydrophobic chemicals associate with the bilayer.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] This property can be utilized to load liposomes with hydrophobic and/or hydrophilic molecules, a process known as encapsulation.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Typically, liposomes are prepared in a solution containing the compound to be trapped, which can either be an aqueous solution for encapsulating hydrophilic compounds like proteins, or solutions in organic solvents mixed with lipids for encapsulating hydrophobic molecules.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Encapsulation techniques can be categorized into two types: passive, which relies on the stochastic trapping of molecules during liposome formation, and active, which relies on the presence of charged lipids or transmembrane ion gradients.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] A crucial parameter to consider is the "encapsulation efficiency," which is defined as the amount of compound present in the liposome solution divided by the total initial amount of compound used during the preparation.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] In more recent developments, the application of liposomes in single-molecule experiments has introduced the concept of "single entity encapsulation efficiency." This term refers to the probability of a specific liposome containing the required number of copies of the compound.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] To deliver the molecules to a site of action, the lipid bilayer can fuse with other bilayers such as the cell membrane, thus delivering the liposome contents; this is a complex and non-spontaneous event, however, that does not apply to nutrients and drug delivery.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] By preparing liposomes in a solution of DNA or drugs (which would normally be unable to diffuse through the membrane) they can be (indiscriminately) delivered past the lipid bilayer.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Liposomes can also be designed to deliver drugs in other ways.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Liposomes that contain low (or high) pH can be constructed such that dissolved aqueous drugs will be charged in solution (i.e., the pH is outside the drug's pI range).
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] As the pH naturally neutralizes within the liposome (protons can pass through some membranes), the drug will also be neutralized, allowing it to freely pass through a membrane.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] These liposomes work to deliver drug by diffusion rather than by direct cell fusion.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] However, the efficacy of this pH regulated passage depends on the physiochemical nature of the drug in question (e.g. pKa and having a basic or acid nature), which is very low for many drugs.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] A similar approach can be exploited in the biodetoxification of drugs by injecting empty liposomes with a transmembrane pH gradient.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] In this case the vesicles act as sinks to scavenge the drug in the blood circulation and prevent its toxic effect.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Another strategy for liposome drug delivery is to target endocytosis events.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Liposomes can be made in a particular size range that makes them viable targets for natural macrophage phagocytosis.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] These liposomes may be digested while in the macrophage's phagosome, thus releasing its drug.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Liposomes can also be decorated with opsonins and ligands to activate endocytosis in other cell types.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] To improve the tolerability of amphotericin and reduce toxicity, researchers developed several lipid formulations.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Liposomal formulations have been found to have less renal toxicity than deoxycholate. and fewer infusion-related reactions.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] AmBisome (liposomal amphotericin B; LAMB) is a liposomal formulation of amphotericin B for injection and consists of a mixture of phosphatidylcholine, cholesterol and distearoyl phosphatidylglycerol that in aqueous media spontaneously arrange into unilamellar vesicles that contain amphotericin B.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] It was developed by NeXstar Pharmaceuticals (acquired by Gilead Sciences in 1999).
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Regarding pH-sensitive liposomes, there are three mechanisms of drug delivery intracellularly, which occurs via endocytosis.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] This is possible because of the acidic environment within endosomes.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] The first mechanism is through the destabilization of the liposome within the endosome, triggering pore formation on the endosomal membrane and allowing diffusion of the liposome and its contents into the cytoplasm.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Another is the release of the encapsulated content within the endosome, eventually diffusing out into the cytoplasm through the endosomal membrane.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Lastly, the membrane of the liposome and the endosome fuse together, releasing the encapsulated contents onto the cytoplasm and avoiding degradation at the lysosomal level due to minimal contact time.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Certain anticancer drugs such as doxorubicin (Doxil) and daunorubicin may be administered encapsulated in liposomes.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Liposomal cisplatin has received orphan drug designation for pancreatic cancer from EMEA.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] A study provides a promising preclinical demonstration of the effectiveness and ease of preparation of valrubicin-loaded immunoliposomes (Val-ILs) as a novel nanoparticle technology.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] In the context of hematological cancers, Val-ILs have the potential to be used as a precise and effective therapy based on targeted vesicle-mediated cell death.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] The use of liposomes for transformation or transfection of DNA into a host cell is known as lipofection.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] In addition to gene and drug delivery applications, liposomes can be used as carriers for the delivery of dyes to textiles, pesticides to plants, enzymes and nutritional supplements to foods, and cosmetics to the skin.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Liposomes are also used as outer shells of some microbubble contrast agents used in contrast-enhanced ultrasound.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Until recently, the clinical uses of liposomes were for targeted drug delivery, but new applications for the oral delivery of certain dietary and nutritional supplements are in development.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] This new application of liposomes is in part due to the low absorption and bioavailability rates of traditional oral dietary and nutritional tablets and capsules.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] The low oral bioavailability and absorption of many nutrients is clinically well documented.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Therefore, the natural encapsulation of lypophilic and hydrophilic nutrients within liposomes would be an effective method of bypassing the destructive elements of the gastric system and small intestines allowing the encapsulated nutrient to be efficiently delivered to the cells and tissues.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] The term nutraceutical combines the words nutrient and pharmaceutical, originally coined by Stephen DeFelice, who defined nutraceuticals as "food or part of a food that provides medical or health benefits, including the prevention and/or treatment of a disease".
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] However, currently, there is no conclusive definition of nutraceuticals yet, to distinguish them from other food‐derived categories, such as food (dietary) supplements, herbal products, pre‐ and probiotics, functional foods, and fortified foods.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Generally, this term is used to describe any product derived from food sources which is expected to provide health benefits additionally to the nutritional value of daily food.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] A wide range of nutrients or other substances with nutritional or physiological effects (EU Directive 2002/46/EC) might be present in these products, including vitamins, minerals, amino acids, essential fatty acids, fibres and various plants and herbal extracts.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Liposomal nutraceuticals contain bioactive compounds with health-promoting effects.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] The encapsulation of bioactive compounds in liposomes is attractive as liposomes have been shown to be able to overcome serious hurdles bioactives would otherwise encounter in the gastrointestinal (GI) tract upon oral intake.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Certain factors have far-reaching effects on the percentage of liposome that are yielded in manufacturing, as well as the actual amount of realized liposome entrapment and the actual quality and long-term stability of the liposomes themselves.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] These are the primary elements in developing effective liposome carriers for use in dietary and nutritional supplements.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Liposomes have also been studied in food science and technology as encapsulation systems for dietary nutrients, nutraceuticals, antimicrobials, probiotics, enzymes, proteins, essential oils, fatty acids, natural colours, flavours and other food additives.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] In this context, liposomal encapsulation is investigated to improve stability, protection during processing or storage, and controlled delivery of bioactive food ingredients.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Useful liposomes rarely form spontaneously.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] They typically form after supplying enough energy to a dispersion of (phospho)lipids in a polar solvent, such as water, to break down multilamellar aggregates into oligo- or unilamellar bilayer vesicles.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Liposomes can hence be created by sonicating a dispersion of amphipatic lipids, such as phospholipids, in water.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Low shear rates create multilamellar liposomes.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] The original aggregates, which have many layers like an onion, thereby form progressively smaller and finally unilamellar liposomes (which are often unstable, owing to their small size and the sonication-created defects).
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Sonication is generally considered a "gross" method of preparation as it can damage the structure of the drug to be encapsulated.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Newer methods such as extrusion, micromixing and Mozafari method are employed to produce materials for human use.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Using lipids other than phosphatidylcholine can greatly facilitate liposome preparation.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] In addition to sonication and extrusion, liposomes can be prepared by controlled-mixing methods, including ethanol injection, microfluidic mixing and other micromixing approaches.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Microfluidic and other continuous-flow mixing methods have become widely used approaches for liposome and lipid-nanoparticle preparation, because they allow controlled mixing, continuous production and improved reproducibility of vesicle size and size distribution.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] However, lipid composition, solvent phase, lipid concentration, flow-rate ratio, total flow rate and post-processing conditions can strongly affect the final vesicle population.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Further advances in liposome research have been able to allow liposomes to avoid detection by the body's immune system, specifically, the cells of reticuloendothelial system (RES).
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] These liposomes are known as "stealth liposomes".
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Blume and, independently and soon thereafter, the groups of L.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Huang and Vladimir Torchilin and are constructed with PEG (Polyethylene Glycol) studding the outside of the membrane.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] The PEG coating, which is inert in the body, allows for longer circulatory life for the drug delivery mechanism.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Studies have also shown that PEGylated liposomes elicit anti-IgM antibodies, thus leading to an enhanced blood clearance of the liposomes upon re-injection, depending on lipid dose and time interval between injections.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] In addition to a PEG coating, some stealth liposomes also have some sort of biological species attached as a ligand to the liposome, to enable binding via a specific expression on the targeted drug delivery site.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] These targeting ligands could be monoclonal antibodies (making an immunoliposome), vitamins, or specific antigens, but must be accessible.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Targeted liposomes can target certain cell type in the body and deliver drugs that would otherwise be systemically delivered.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Naturally toxic drugs can be much less systemically toxic if delivered only to diseased tissues.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Polymersomes, morphologically related to liposomes, can also be used this way.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Also morphologically related to liposomes are highly deformable vesicles, designed for non-invasive transdermal material delivery, known as transfersomes.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Liposomes are used as models for artificial cells.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Liposomes can be used on their own or in combination with traditional antibiotics as neutralizing agents of bacterial toxins.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Many bacterial toxins evolved to target specific lipids of the host cells membrane and can be baited and neutralized by liposomes containing those specific lipid targets.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] A study published in May 2018 also explored the potential use of liposomes as "nano-carriers" of fertilizing nutrients to treat malnourished or sickly plants.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Results showed that these synthetic particles "soak into plant leaves more easily than naked nutrients", further validating the utilization of nanotechnology to increase crop yields.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Machine learning has started to contribute to liposome research.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] For example, deep learning was used to monitor a multistep bioassay containing sucrose-loaded and nucleotides-loaded liposomes interacting with a lipid membrane-perforating peptide.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/liposome] Artificial neural networks were also used to optimize formulation parameters of leuprolide acetate loaded liposomes and to predict the particle size and the polydispersity index of liposomes.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] A **micelle** (/maɪˈsɛl/; also spelled **micell**) or **micella** (/maɪˈsɛlə/) (pl.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] **micelles** or **micellae**, respectively) is an aggregate (or supramolecular assembly) of surfactant amphipathic lipid molecules dispersed in a liquid, forming a colloidal suspension (also known as associated colloidal system).
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] A typical micelle in water forms an aggregate, with the hydrophilic "head" regions in contact with surrounding solvent, sequestering the hydrophobic single-tail regions in the micelle centre.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] This phase is caused by the packing behavior of single-tail lipids in a bilayer.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] The difficulty in filling the volume of the interior of a bilayer, while accommodating the area per head group forced on the molecule by the hydration of the lipid head group, leads to the formation of the micelle.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] This type of micelle is known as a normal-phase micelle (or oil-in-water micelle).
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Inverse micelles have the head groups at the centre with the tails extending out (or water-in-oil micelle).
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Micelles are approximately spherical in shape.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Other shapes, such as ellipsoids, cylinders, and bilayers, are also possible.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] The shape and size of a micelle are a function of the molecular geometry of its surfactant molecules and solution conditions such as surfactant concentration, temperature, pH, and ionic strength.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] The process of forming micelles is known as micellisation and forms part of the phase behaviour of many lipids according to their polymorphism.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] The ability of a soapy solution to act as a detergent has been recognized for centuries.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] However, it was only at the beginning of the twentieth century that the constitution of such solutions was scientifically studied.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Pioneering work in this area was carried out by James William McBain at the University of Bristol.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] As early as 1913, he postulated the existence of "colloidal ions" to explain the good electrolytic conductivity of sodium palmitate solutions.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] These highly mobile, spontaneously formed clusters came to be called micelles, a term borrowed from biology and popularized by G.S.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Hartley in his classic book *Paraffin Chain Salts: A Study in Micelle Formation*.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] The term *micelle* was coined in nineteenth century scientific literature as the *‑elle* diminutive of the Latin word *mica* (particle), conveying a new word for "tiny particle".
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Individual surfactant molecules that are in the system but are not part of a micelle are called "monomers".
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Micelles represent a molecular assembly, in which the individual components are thermodynamically in equilibrium with monomers of the same species in the surrounding medium.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] In water, the hydrophilic "heads" of surfactant molecules are always in contact with the solvent, regardless of whether the surfactants exist as monomers or as part of a micelle.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] However, the lipophilic "tails" of surfactant molecules have less contact with water when they are part of a micelle—this being the basis for the energetic drive for micelle formation.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] In a micelle, the hydrophobic tails of several surfactant molecules assemble into an oil-like core, the most stable form of which having no contact with water.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] By contrast, surfactant monomers are surrounded by water molecules that create a "cage" or solvation shell connected by hydrogen bonds.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] This water cage is similar to a clathrate and has an ice-like crystal structure and can be characterized according to the hydrophobic effect.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] The extent of lipid solubility is determined by the unfavorable entropy contribution due to the ordering of the water structure according to the hydrophobic effect.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Micelles composed of ionic surfactants have an electrostatic attraction to the ions that surround them in solution, the latter known as counterions.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Although the closest counterions partially mask a charged micelle (by up to 92%), the effects of micelle charge affect the structure of the surrounding solvent at appreciable distances from the micelle.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Ionic micelles influence many properties of the mixture, including its electrical conductivity.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Adding salts to a colloid containing micelles can decrease the strength of electrostatic interactions and lead to the formation of larger ionic micelles.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] This is more accurately seen from the point of view of an effective charge in hydration of the system.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Micelles form only when the concentration of surfactant is greater than the critical micelle concentration (CMC), and the temperature of the system is greater than the critical micelle temperature, or Krafft temperature.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] The formation of micelles can be understood using thermodynamics: Micelles can form spontaneously because of a balance between entropy and enthalpy.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] In water, the hydrophobic effect is the driving force for micelle formation, despite the fact that assembling surfactant molecules is unfavorable in terms of both enthalpy and entropy of the system.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] At very low concentrations of the surfactant, only monomers are present in solution.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] As the concentration of the surfactant is increased, a point is reached at which the unfavorable entropy contribution, from clustering the hydrophobic tails of the molecules, is overcome by a gain in entropy due to release of the solvation shells around the surfactant tails.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] At this point, the lipid tails of a part of the surfactants must be segregated from the water.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] In broad terms, above the CMC, the loss of entropy due to assembly of the surfactant molecules is less than the gain in entropy by setting free the water molecules that were "trapped" in the solvation shells of the surfactant monomers.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Also important are enthalpic considerations, such as the electrostatic interactions that occur between the charged parts of surfactants.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] where $v_{o}$ is the surfactant tail volume, $\ell _{o}$ is the tail length, and $a_{e}$ is the equilibrium area per molecule at the aggregate surface.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] The concept of micelles was introduced to describe the core-corona aggregates of small surfactant molecules, however it has also extended to describe aggregates of amphiphilic block copolymers in selective solvents.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] It is important to know the difference between these two systems.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] The major difference between these two types of aggregates is in the size of their building blocks.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Surfactant molecules have a molecular weight which is generally of a few hundreds of grams per mole while block copolymers are generally one or two orders of magnitude larger.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Moreover, thanks to the larger hydrophilic and hydrophobic parts, block copolymers can have a much more pronounced amphiphilic nature when compared to surfactant molecules.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Because of these differences in the building blocks, some block copolymer micelles behave like surfactant ones, while others do not.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] It is necessary therefore to make a distinction between the two situations.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Certain amphiphilic block copolymer micelles display a similar behavior as surfactant micelles.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] These are generally called dynamic micelles and are characterized by the same relaxation processes assigned to surfactant exchange and micelle scission/recombination.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Although the relaxation processes are the same between the two types of micelles, the kinetics of unimer exchange are very different.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] While in surfactant systems the unimers leave and join the micelles through a diffusion-controlled process, for copolymers the entry rate constant is slower than a diffusion controlled process.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] The rate of this process was found to be a decreasing power-law of the degree of polymerization of the hydrophobic block to the power 2/3.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] This difference is due to the coiling of the hydrophobic block of a copolymer exiting the core of a micelle.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Block copolymers which form dynamic micelles are some of the tri-block poloxamers under the right conditions.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] When block copolymer micelles do not display the characteristic relaxation processes of surfactant micelles, these are called *kinetically frozen micelles*.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] These can be achieved in two ways: when the unimers forming the micelles are not soluble in the solvent of the micelle solution, or if the core forming blocks are glassy at the temperature in which the micelles are found.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Kinetically frozen micelles are formed when either of these conditions is met.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] A special example in which both of these conditions are valid is that of polystyrene-b-poly(ethylene oxide).
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] This block copolymer is characterized by the high hydrophobicity of the core forming block, PS, which causes the unimers to be insoluble in water.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Moreover, PS has a high glass transition temperature which is, depending on the molecular weight, higher than room temperature.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Thanks to these two characteristics, a water solution of PS-PEO micelles of sufficiently high molecular weight can be considered kinetically frozen.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] This means that none of the relaxation processes, which would drive the micelle solution towards thermodynamic equilibrium, are possible.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Pioneering work on these micelles was done by Adi Eisenberg.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] It was also shown how the lack of relaxation processes allowed great freedom in the possible morphologies formed.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Moreover, the stability against dilution and vast range of morphologies of kinetically frozen micelles make them particularly interesting, for example, for the development of long circulating drug delivery nanoparticles.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] In a non-polar solvent, it is the exposure of the hydrophilic head groups to the surrounding solvent that is energetically unfavourable, giving rise to a water-in-oil system.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] In this case, the hydrophilic groups are sequestered in the micelle core and the hydrophobic groups extend away from the center.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] These inverse micelles are proportionally less likely to form on increasing headgroup charge, since hydrophilic sequestration would create highly unfavorable electrostatic interactions.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] It is well established that for many surfactant/solvent systems a small fraction of the inverse micelles spontaneously acquire a net charge of +qe or -qe.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] This charging takes place through a disproportionation/comproportionation mechanism rather than a dissociation/association mechanism and the equilibrium constant for this reaction is on the order of 10−4 to 10−11, which means about every 1 in 100 to 1 in 100 000 micelles will be charged.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Supermicelle is a hierarchical micelle structure (supramolecular assembly) where individual components are also micelles.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] The stems of the primary cylindrical micelles are composed of various block copolymers connected by strong covalent bonds; within the supermicelle structure they are loosely held together by hydrogen bonds, electrostatic or solvophobic interactions.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] When surfactants are present above the critical micelle concentration (CMC), they can act as emulsifiers that will allow a compound that is normally insoluble (in the solvent being used) to dissolve.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] This occurs because the insoluble species can be incorporated into the micelle core, which is itself solubilized in the bulk solvent by virtue of the head groups' favorable interactions with solvent species.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] The most common example of this phenomenon is detergents, which clean poorly soluble lipophilic material (such as oils and waxes) that cannot be removed by water alone.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Detergents clean also by lowering the surface tension of water, making it easier to remove material from a surface.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] The emulsifying property of surfactants is also the basis for emulsion polymerization.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Micelles may also have important roles in chemical reactions.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Micellar chemistry uses the interior of micelles to harbor chemical reactions, which in some cases can make multi-step chemical synthesis more feasible.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Doing so can increase reaction yield, create conditions more favorable to specific reaction products (e.g. hydrophobic molecules), and reduce required solvents, side products, and required conditions (e.g. extreme pH).
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Because of these benefits, Micellular chemistry is thus considered a form of green chemistry.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] However, micelle formation may also inhibit chemical reactions, such as when reacting molecules form micelles that shield a molecular component vulnerable to oxidation.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] The use of cationic micelles of cetrimonium chloride, benzethonium chloride, and cetylpyridinium chloride can accelerate chemical reactions between negatively charged compounds (such as DNA or Coenzyme A) in an aqueous environment up to 5 million times.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Unlike conventional micellar catalysis, the reactions occur solely on the charged micelles' surface.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Micelle formation is essential for the absorption of fat-soluble vitamins and complicated lipids within the human body.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Bile salts formed in the liver and secreted by the gall bladder allow micelles of fatty acids to form.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] This allows the absorption of complicated lipids (e.g., lecithin) and lipid-soluble vitamins (A, D, E, and K) within the micelle by the small intestine.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] During the process of milk-clotting, proteases act on the soluble portion of caseins, κ-casein, thus originating an unstable micellar state that results in clot formation.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/micelle] Micelles can also be used for targeted drug delivery as gold nanoparticles.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] A **transdermal patch** is a medicated adhesive patch that is placed on the skin to deliver a specific dose of medication through the skin and into the bloodstream.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] The main disadvantage to transdermal delivery systems stems from the fact that the skin is a very effective barrier; as a result, only medications whose molecules are small enough to penetrate the skin can be delivered by this method.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] The first commercially available prescription patch was approved by the U.S.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Food and Drug Administration in December 1979.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] These patches administered scopolamine for motion sickness.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] MNPs offer the advantage of controlled release of medication and simple application without medical professional assistance required.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] With advanced MNPs technology, drug delivery can be specified for local usage, for example skin whitener MNPs that are applied to the face.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Many types of MNPs have been developed to penetrate tissues other than skin, such as internal tissues of the mouth and digestive tract.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] These promote faster and more direct delivery of the molecule to the targeted area.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Other components include stabilizers (antioxidants), preservatives, etc.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] There are five main types of transdermal patches.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] The adhesive layer of this system also contains the drug.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] In this type of patch the adhesive layer not only serves to adhere the various layers together, along with the entire system to the skin, but is also responsible for the releasing of the drug.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] The adhesive layer is surrounded by a temporary liner and a backing.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] It is characterized by the inclusion of the drug directly within the skin-contacting adhesive placed onto the epidermis.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] The multi-layer drug-in-adhesive patch is similar to the single-layer system; the multi-layer system is different, however, in that it adds another layer of drug-in-adhesive, usually separated by a membrane (but not in all cases).
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] One of the layers is for immediate release of the drug, and the other layer is for controlled release of the drug from the reservoir.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] This patch also has a temporary liner-layer and a permanent backing.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] The drug release from this depends on membrane permeability and diffusion of drug molecules.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Unlike the single-layer and multi-layer drug-in-adhesive systems, the reservoir transdermal system has a separate drug layer.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] The drug layer is a liquid compartment containing a drug solution or suspension separated by the adhesive layer.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] The drug reservoir is totally encapsulated in a shallow compartment molded from a drug-impermeable metallic plastic laminate, with a rate-controlling membrane made of a polymer like vinyl acetate on one surface.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] This patch is also backed by the backing layer.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] In this type of system the rate of release is zero order.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Reservoir patches should not be cut (with the exception of hyoscine hyrdobromide 1.5mg patch according to the British National Formulary for Children).
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] The matrix system has a drug layer of a semisolid matrix containing a drug solution or suspension.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] The adhesive layer in this patch surrounds the drug layer, partially overlaying it.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] The release rate is determined by the physical properties of the matrix.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Limited research indicates that it may be possible to cut some matrix patches to provide lower doses, provided the cut part not immediately used is stored at cool temperatures.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] In a vapour patch, the adhesive layer not only serves to adhere the various layers together but also to release vapour.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Vapour patches release essential oils for up to 6 hours and are mainly used for decongestion.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Other vapour patches on the market improve quality of sleep or aid in smoking cessation.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] The microneedle patch (MNPs) is a type of transdermal patch which retains the advantages, but reduces the disadvantages of basic transdermal patches.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Embedding as many as 102–104 needles per square centimetre of patch, encapsulated or coated with intended drug, MNPs can easily pass skin tissue known as the stratum corneum which is roughly 20 μm in thickness, allowing up to the size of macromolecule to pass.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] MNPs were developed mainly because transdermal patch can deliver smaller size or micronized molecules such as nicotine and birth control which easily diffuse and penetrate the skin, but lack in delivering macro or large size molecules.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] The 100–1000 μm needles spread across the patch, making sure people will not feel any discomfort from the patch.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] There are two types of needles used in MNPs, the first one is non-water-soluble needles made out of metal, ceramic, or polymer, and the second one is water-soluble needles made out of saccharides or soluble polymers.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] MNPs can also be engineered to deliver molecules into other tissues.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Some that as of 2018 have been under development include internal surfaces such as the mouth, vagina, gastrointestinal tract, and vascular wall; and external surfaces such as the skin, eyes, fingernails, anus, and scalp.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] As mentioned earlier, MNPs deliver more efficient delivery compared to topical or oral intake.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] In drug delivery study, researchers want to gain faster peak concentrations (Cmax) in MNPs compared to other methods.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Study shows that MNPs reach peak concentration as fast as 20 minutes (tmax), while oral intake reaches peak concentration in one hour.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Furthermore, the Cmax from MNPs is higher up to six times, compared to oral intake.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Making the delivery fast and the body gets the most concentration of intended drugs.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] This value is only matched with direct injection, but with skin trauma and people with needle phobia, MNPs might be an alternative to reach roughly the same time and concentration.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] In order to get more direct local delivery, MNPs can be used in different tissues other than the skin.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] In **Table 1**, there are at least five internal surfaces that MNPs have been studied for its delivery and four other external surfaces other than the skin.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] There are many types of microneedle that are distinguished by the shape and other characteristics.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] The types include: Dissolvable MNPs, solid non-soluble MNPs, and hollow MNPs.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Different MNPs may be chosen depending on the situation and the drug properties.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] One of the types of MNPs are water-soluble needles made out of soluble polymers or saccharide.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] However, dissolvable needles cannot efficiently deliver drugs to the dermal layer.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Drug maximum concentration cannot be carried out to the skin, as the needles will dissolve beforehand.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Fortunately, researchers have developed a water-insoluble backing layer, making the needle last longer in the human body environment.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] This design enables efficient delivery of more than 90% of the drug within 5 minutes of application of MNPs to the skin.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Other than dissolvable MNPs, needles can also be made out of metal or ceramic that will not dissolve in the body environment.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] These coated drug needles can deliver consistent concentration of drugs without the needles dissolving in the body.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] This kind of MNPs has better performance, but compared to the soluble MNPs, metal or ceramic MNPs are the older version of MNPs.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Even if the patches are small, the metal or ceramic MNPs may cause several waste issues.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Recycling the metal and ceramic are very hard, as the quantity is very small to overcome the cost to recycle.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] That is why researchers try to develop the dissolvable MNPs with similar characteristic and performance of drug delivery in non-soluble MNPs.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Among all of the MNPs, hollow needles allow a bigger amount of delivery up to 200μL.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] The mechanism mimics the operation of a hypodermic, but the fabrication is hard and complex.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] The hollow needles introduce a potential failure if the insertion is improper.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] That is why, among the others, hollow MNPs are the least popular because of the complex manufacturing and applying process.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Can be localized to provide direct access to the intended tissues.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Less dependent on skilled medical workers, as MNPs can be administered safely by the patient themself.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Some drugs have poor solubility in water, with MNPs insoluble drugs and compounds can be directly "injected" to the dermal layer.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Further enhancing the transdermal delivery of insoluble drugs.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Better safety compared to needle and syringe method (needlestick).
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Less waste, eliminate pathogen transmission, and injuries.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] At least 300,000 needlestick related injuries occurred in the US annually, with disposal contributing to almost half of the injuries.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] MNPs vaccination might be an alternative from direct injection.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Able to deliver bigger molecules than transdermal patch, MNPs can also deliver bioactive molecules with different physical sizes.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Meaning that inactive virus or pathogen can be introduced in the body without discomfort or skin irritation from conventional injection.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Possibly it can also reduce the cost of storage that usually needs to be transported in a particular temperature and condition.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Stated in cdc.gov website, Mark Prausnitz, co-developer of the microneedle, says "A major advantage of the microneedle patch would be the ease of delivery." The MNPs are small and thin compared to bottles of vial, making it possible to transport in massive quantities in a single trip.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Medical waste such as syringes and dirty needles are also eliminated, reducing the possibility of pathogen transmission of blood-borne disease in rural areas.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] In a study, measles coated MNPs might be resistant to higher temperature compared to vial transport.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Higher temperature resistance is a safe bet in low income countries, where there is no such luxury for refrigeration.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Furthermore, the delivery of the vaccine is controlled by the MNPs.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Less requiring highly trained medical workers in developing countries to apply the vaccine.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Skin treatment including face whitening agent and dark eye circles serum can also incorporated in MNPs.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Its localized property enhance skin whitening delivery to the face area.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Even a very specific spot like dark eye circles.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] By measuring the melanin (dark or black pigment found on the skin) index, subjects that are treated with whitening agents coated in MNPs show lower melanin index, compared to the whitening essence (topical) group.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] The treatment lasts for eight weeks, and the result shows MNPs might be a promising cosmetic vector because MNPs does not introduce skin irritation and can be engineered to localize or specific parts of the body.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] MNPs may cause skin irritation on people with sensitive skin.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Majority of studies show that MNPs do not irritate the skin.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Especially for hollow MNPs, the not so stiff needles may cause unnecessary puncture of the skin outer layer, and may cause trauma to the skin and restricting the performance and flow of the drugs to the body.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Because most of MNPs applications are still under development, it is important to note the long effect of the efficiency of the drug deliveries.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] More research is needed to get information of what molecule can be delivered using MNPs.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Disposal is also an important topic, as the small plastic backing may contribute to water pollution remembering the compact size can be easily carried away by wind and water without proper disposal.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] A transdermal patch is classified by the U.S.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Food and Drug Administration as a *combination product*, consisting of a medical device combined with a drug or biological product that the device is designed to deliver.
[src:drug-delivery-systems/transdermal-patch] Prior to sale in the United States, any transdermal patch product must apply for and receive approval from the Food and Drug Administration, demonstrating safety and efficacy for its intended use.
